The paper deals with algorithmic techniques for solving various problems in planar graphs, which are a fundamental topic in computer science. The use of dynamic programming and tree-width decomposition suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The focus on planar graphs and related problems such as connectivity, diameter, girth, and shortest paths suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. The use of graph theory and combinatorics in analyzing the complexity of the algorithms suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. The study of subgraph isomorphism and induced subgraph isomorphism suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.GT (Graph Theory) sub-category. Finally, the use of dynamic programming and optimization techniques suggests that the paper may also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category, which often deals with similar algorithmic problems.
